<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="160" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,151,1328]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,337,188,213]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">Description</emphasis>
. Thinly encrusting sponge 
<quantity box="[642,756,188,213]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.25" metricValueMax="2.0" metricValueMin="0.5" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" unit="mm" value="1.25" valueMax="2.0" valueMin="0.5">0.5–2 mm</quantity>
thickness, adhered to bryozoan and pieces of coral (
<figureCitation box="[1341,1407,188,213]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1227,1249]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1205]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1436,193,1206]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 7. Spirastrella aff. mollis Verrill, 1907: A. Specimen preserved in alcohol growing on Briozoan. B. Skeletal arrangement in cross section, in which appears the spiraster cortex above (dark fringe area) and a palisade of tylostyle tufts underneath. C. Common tylostyle head in SEM. D. Size relationship between the two categories of spirasters. E. Spiraster II. F. Spiraster I." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/238822/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">
Fig. 
<number box="[1393,1407,188,212]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" value="7.0">7</number>
</figureCitation>
A) making a cavernous whole mass 
<quantity box="[520,596,224,248]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.3" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" unit="cm" value="4.3">4.3 cm</quantity>
long and 
<quantity box="[708,784,223,248]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.6" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" unit="cm" value="2.6">2.6 cm</quantity>
in width. The surface is smooth as well as microhispid on mounds in all around the mass, velvety in appearance but harsh when touched, becoming strongly hispid underneath the coral rubble or in hidden fissures or holes, no oscules nor pores visible to the naked eye in preserved specimens. The consistency is difficult to know owing to the thinness of the sponge, but the sponge is not easily compressible due to the many small conch fragments within the flesh. Color alive not recorded, unfortunately, no photograph 
<emphasis box="[285,354,405,428]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">in situ</emphasis>
was taken, and color in alcohol is beige.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,151,1328]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,302,439,464]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">Skeleton</emphasis>
. The ectosome has a thin cortex 
<number box="[672,714,440,464]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" value="200.0">200</number>
µm thick that consists mainly of spirasters and tips of tylostyles protruding up to 
<number box="[352,394,476,500]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" value="140.0">140</number>
µm beyond the surface. The narrow area of the choanosome is formed by a palisade of tylostyles tufts with the tips directed upwards, below which, spirasters are abundant everywhere (
<figureCitation box="[1259,1328,511,536]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1227,1249]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1205]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1436,193,1206]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 7. Spirastrella aff. mollis Verrill, 1907: A. Specimen preserved in alcohol growing on Briozoan. B. Skeletal arrangement in cross section, in which appears the spiraster cortex above (dark fringe area) and a palisade of tylostyle tufts underneath. C. Common tylostyle head in SEM. D. Size relationship between the two categories of spirasters. E. Spiraster II. F. Spiraster I." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/238822/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">
Fig. 
<number box="[1313,1328,512,536]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" value="7.0">7</number>
</figureCitation>
B). Small and round channels were seen below the cortex.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,151,1328]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,297,583,608]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">Spicules</emphasis>
. Macroscleres are straight and slightly curved tylostyles with fusiform tips 
<number box="[1171,1270,583,608]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" value="442.0" valueMax="624.0" valueMin="260.0">260–624</number>
× 
<number box="[1304,1381,584,608]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" value="10.9" valueMax="14.0" valueMin="7.8">7.8–14</number>
µm, mainly with a round head but oval-shaped are also present 
<number box="[813,883,620,645]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" value="13.5" valueMax="15.0" valueMin="12.0">12–15</number>
µm in diameter (
<figureCitation box="[1078,1146,620,645]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1227,1249]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1205]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1436,193,1206]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 7. Spirastrella aff. mollis Verrill, 1907: A. Specimen preserved in alcohol growing on Briozoan. B. Skeletal arrangement in cross section, in which appears the spiraster cortex above (dark fringe area) and a palisade of tylostyle tufts underneath. C. Common tylostyle head in SEM. D. Size relationship between the two categories of spirasters. E. Spiraster II. F. Spiraster I." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/238822/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">
Fig. 
<number box="[1131,1146,620,644]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" value="7.0">7</number>
</figureCitation>
C), few ones with annular swelling bellow the neck. Microscleres are spirasters approaching amphiasters in two size categories (
<figureCitation box="[1290,1351,655,680]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1227,1249]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1205]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1436,193,1206]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 7. Spirastrella aff. mollis Verrill, 1907: A. Specimen preserved in alcohol growing on Briozoan. B. Skeletal arrangement in cross section, in which appears the spiraster cortex above (dark fringe area) and a palisade of tylostyle tufts underneath. C. Common tylostyle head in SEM. D. Size relationship between the two categories of spirasters. E. Spiraster II. F. Spiraster I." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/238822/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">
Fig. 
<number box="[1337,1351,655,680]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" value="7.0">7</number>
</figureCitation>
D): size I is 
<number box="[195,285,692,717]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" value="38.9" valueMax="57.0" valueMin="20.8">20.8–57</number>
µm long (
<figureCitation box="[405,466,692,717]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1227,1249]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1205]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1436,193,1206]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 7. Spirastrella aff. mollis Verrill, 1907: A. Specimen preserved in alcohol growing on Briozoan. B. Skeletal arrangement in cross section, in which appears the spiraster cortex above (dark fringe area) and a palisade of tylostyle tufts underneath. C. Common tylostyle head in SEM. D. Size relationship between the two categories of spirasters. E. Spiraster II. F. Spiraster I." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/238822/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">
Fig 
<number box="[451,466,692,716]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" value="7.0">7</number>
</figureCitation>
F), it bends once to twice but it is difficult to discern, its rays are conical up to 
<number box="[1362,1390,692,716]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" value="20.0">20</number>
µm long with broad bases from about 
<number box="[544,579,727,752]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" value="5.2">5.2</number>
µm; size II is 
<number box="[749,826,727,752]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" value="15.7" valueMax="26.0" valueMin="5.4">5.4–26</number>
µm long (
<figureCitation box="[948,1016,727,752]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1227,1249]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1205]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1436,193,1206]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 7. Spirastrella aff. mollis Verrill, 1907: A. Specimen preserved in alcohol growing on Briozoan. B. Skeletal arrangement in cross section, in which appears the spiraster cortex above (dark fringe area) and a palisade of tylostyle tufts underneath. C. Common tylostyle head in SEM. D. Size relationship between the two categories of spirasters. E. Spiraster II. F. Spiraster I." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/238822/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">
Fig. 
<number box="[1002,1016,728,752]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" value="7.0">7</number>
</figureCitation>
E), it shows a slender shaft in one to three bends sometimes straight, with smaller conical rays (sizes including spines).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="160" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,151,1328]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,491,799,824]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">Distribution and ecology</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName box="[505,607,799,824]" class="Demospongiae" family="Chondropsidae" genus="Strongylacidon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Poecilosclerida" pageId="9" pageNumber="180" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="bermuda">
<collectingCountry box="[505,607,799,824]" name="Bermuda" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">Bermuda</collectingCountry>
</taxonomicName>
<collectingCountry box="[614,685,799,824]" name="Iceland" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">Island</collectingCountry>
, intertidal to 
<quantity box="[834,898,799,824]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" unit="m" value="0.5">0.5 m</quantity>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Verrill" box="[912,1052,799,824]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" refString="Verrill, A. E. (1907) The Bermuda Islands: Part V. An account of Coral Reefs. Porifera: Sponges. Transactions of the Connecticut Academy of Arts and Sciences, 12, 330 - 344." type="journal article" year="1907">
Verrill 
<number box="[992,1052,800,824]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" value="1907.0">1907</number>
</bibRefCitation>
), Carrie Bow Cay, 
<collectingCountry box="[1266,1338,799,824]" name="Belize" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">Belize</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Rutzler" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" refString="Rutzler, K., Piatoni, C., Soest van, R. W. M. &amp; Diaz, M. C. (2014) Diversity of sponges (Porifera) from cryptic habitats on the Belize barrier reef near Carrie Bow Cay. Zootaxa, 3805, 1 - 129. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3805.1.1" type="journal article" year="2014">
Rützler 
<emphasis box="[151,208,836,861]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">et al.</emphasis>
<number box="[216,276,836,860]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" value="2014.0">2014</number>
</bibRefCitation>
), now in Yucatan, 
<collectingCountry box="[489,574,836,861]" name="Mexico" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">México</collectingCountry>
coral reefs from the present work. Hence, first record of the species for the Gulf of 
<collectingCountry box="[239,328,871,896]" name="Mexico" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">Mexico</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="160" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,151,1328]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,908,933]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">Remarks</emphasis>
. There is some controversy around 
<taxonomicName box="[729,939,908,933]" class="Demospongiae" family="Spirastrellidae" genus="Spirastrella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hadromerida" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="mollis">
<emphasis box="[729,939,908,933]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">Spirastrella mollis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
due to a brief original description, lack of spicular measurements and loss of the type-specimen (
<bibRefCitation author="Boury-Esnault" box="[768,1066,943,968]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" refString="Boury-Esnault, N., Klatau, M., Bezac, C., Wulff, J. &amp; Sole-Cava, A. M. (1999) Comparative study of putative conspecific sponge populations from both sides of the Isthmus of Panama. Journal of the Marine Biological Association of the United Kingdom, 79, 39 - 50. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1017 / S 0025315498000046" type="journal article" year="1999">
Boury-Esnault 
<emphasis box="[941,998,943,968]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">et al.</emphasis>
<number box="[1006,1066,944,968]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" value="1999.0">1999</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). The spirasters of 
<emphasis box="[1283,1387,943,968]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">
<taxonomicName box="[1283,1383,943,968]" class="Demospongiae" family="Spirastrellidae" genus="Spirastrella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hadromerida" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="mollis">S. mollis</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
and also in 
<taxonomicName box="[234,363,981,1004]" class="Demospongiae" family="Spirastrellidae" genus="Spirastrella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hadromerida" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="coccinea">
<emphasis box="[234,363,981,1004]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">S. coccinea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the plates of 
<bibRefCitation box="[547,779,980,1005]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" refString="Rutzler, K., Piatoni, C., Soest van, R. W. M. &amp; Diaz, M. C. (2014) Diversity of sponges (Porifera) from cryptic habitats on the Belize barrier reef near Carrie Bow Cay. Zootaxa, 3805, 1 - 129. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3805.1.1" type="journal article">
Rützler 
<emphasis box="[637,694,980,1005]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">et al.</emphasis>
(
<number box="[710,771,980,1004]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" value="2014.0">2014</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
, are quite different from the present specimen, suggesting existence of three different species, 
<emphasis box="[561,811,1015,1040]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">
<taxonomicName box="[561,693,1016,1040]" class="Demospongiae" family="Spirastrellidae" genus="Spirastrella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hadromerida" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="coccinea">S. coccinea</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[706,807,1015,1040]" class="Demospongiae" family="Spirastrellidae" genus="Spirastrella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hadromerida" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="mollis">S. mollis</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[869,1001,1015,1040]" class="Demospongiae" family="Spirastrellidae" genus="Spirastrella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hadromerida" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="hartmani">
<emphasis box="[869,1001,1015,1040]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">S. hartmani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The latter, corresponds to the furcate and plurifid spirasters (
<bibRefCitation author="Boury-Esnault" box="[409,704,1052,1077]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" refString="Boury-Esnault, N., Klatau, M., Bezac, C., Wulff, J. &amp; Sole-Cava, A. M. (1999) Comparative study of putative conspecific sponge populations from both sides of the Isthmus of Panama. Journal of the Marine Biological Association of the United Kingdom, 79, 39 - 50. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1017 / S 0025315498000046" type="journal article" year="1999">
Boury-Esnault 
<emphasis box="[581,637,1052,1077]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">et al.</emphasis>
<number box="[644,704,1052,1076]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" value="1999.0">1999</number>
</bibRefCitation>
), not in synonymy with 
<taxonomicName box="[976,1073,1052,1077]" class="Demospongiae" family="Spirastrellidae" genus="Spirastrella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hadromerida" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="mollis">
<emphasis box="[976,1073,1052,1077]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">S. mollis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,151,1328]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">
Four species of 
<taxonomicName box="[381,512,1087,1112]" class="Demospongiae" family="Spirastrellidae" genus="Spirastrella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hadromerida" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[381,512,1087,1112]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">Spirastrella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have been recorded in the Gulf of 
<collectingCountry box="[915,1001,1087,1112]" name="Mexico" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">Mexico</collectingCountry>
and adjacent waters, so far. These are 
<taxonomicName authority="Duchassaing &amp; Michelotti 1864" authorityName="Duchassaing &amp; Michelotti" authorityYear="1864" box="[151,785,1124,1149]" class="Demospongiae" family="Spirastrellidae" genus="Spirastrella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hadromerida" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="coccinea">
<emphasis box="[151,391,1124,1149]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">Spirastrella coccinea</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Duchassaing" box="[407,777,1124,1149]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" refString="Duchassaing, F. P. &amp; Michelotti, G. (1864) Spongiaires de la mer Caraibe. Natuurkundige verhandelingen van de Hollandsche maatschappij der wetenschappen te Haarlem, 21, 1 - 24." type="journal article" year="1864">
Duchassaing &amp; Michelotti 
<number box="[717,777,1124,1149]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" value="1864.0">1864</number>
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[798,959,1125,1148]" class="Demospongiae" family="Spirastrellidae" genus="Spirastrella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hadromerida" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="coccinopsis">
<emphasis box="[798,959,1125,1148]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">S. coccinopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
de 
<bibRefCitation author="Laubenfels" box="[1003,1202,1124,1149]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" refString="Laubenfels, M. W. de (1953) Sponges from the Gulf of Mexico. Bulletin of Marine Science Gulf and Caribbean, 2, 511 - 557." type="journal article" year="1953">
Laubenfels, 
<number box="[1143,1202,1124,1149]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" value="1953.0">1953</number>
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[1215,1347,1124,1149]" class="Demospongiae" family="Spirastrellidae" genus="Spirastrella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hadromerida" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="hartmani">
<emphasis box="[1215,1347,1124,1149]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">S. hartmani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Boury- Esnault 
<emphasis box="[242,299,1159,1184]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">et al.</emphasis>
<number box="[306,364,1160,1184]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" value="1999.0">1999</number>
, and 
<taxonomicName box="[424,521,1159,1184]" class="Demospongiae" family="Spirastrellidae" genus="Spirastrella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hadromerida" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="mollis">
<emphasis box="[424,521,1159,1184]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">S. mollis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The task to tell them apart to correctly identify the species is intricate due to the shared and overlapping traits. For example, the spicule geometry and skeletal arrangement are very similar among all four species. They all have similar sizes, and very little data available other than the original descriptions. In an attempt to delimit differences within some 
<taxonomicName box="[637,769,1268,1293]" class="Demospongiae" family="Spirastrellidae" genus="Spirastrella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hadromerida" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[637,769,1268,1293]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">Spirastrella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species, a comparison was made from the present material and three spirastrellas sheltered in the 
<collectionCode box="[580,675,1304,1328]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">CNPGG</collectionCode>
, which are different indeed (see 
<tableCitation box="[1039,1121,1303,1328]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="9.[151,239,1376,1399]" captionTargetBox="[159,1417,1530,1942]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="TABLE 1. Comparison of taxonomic features among Spirastrella mollis, S. coccinea and S. hartmani sheltered in the CNPGG." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/DF6DE3D7606CFFDFFF54D66A81FAB8E1" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" tableUuid="DF6DE3D7606CFFDFFF54D66A81FAB8E1">
Table 
<number box="[1108,1121,1304,1328]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" value="1.0">1</number>
</tableCitation>
).
</paragraph>
